# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-transformation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The term high-altitude wind power (HAWP) has been used to refer to AWE systems.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] However, semantically HAWP might also include wind energy conversion systems that are somehow positioned at a large height from the ground or sea surface.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Various mechanisms are proposed for capturing the kinetic energy of winds such as kites, kytoons, aerostats, gliders, gliders with turbines for regenerative soaring, sailplanes with turbines, or other airfoils, including multiple-point building- or terrain-enabled holdings.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Once the mechanical energy is derived from the wind's kinetic energy, then many options are available for using that mechanical energy: direct traction, conversion to electricity aloft or at ground station, conversion to laser or microwave for power beaming to other aircraft or ground receivers.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Winds at higher altitudes become steadier, more persistent, and of higher velocity.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Because power available in wind increases as the cube of velocity (the velocity-cubed law), assuming other parameters remaining the same, doubling a wind's velocity gives 23=8 times the power; tripling the velocity gives 33=27 times the available power.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] With steadier and more predictable winds, high-altitude wind has an advantage over wind near the ground.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Being able to locate HAWP to effective altitudes and using the vertical dimension of airspace for wind farming brings further advantage using high-altitude winds for generating energy.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] High-altitude wind generators can be adjusted in height and position to maximize energy return, which is impractical with fixed tower-mounted wind generators.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] In each range of altitudes there are altitude-specific concerns being addressed by researchers and developers.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] As altitude increases, tethers increase in length, the temperature of the air changes, and vulnerability to atmospheric lightning changes.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] With increasing altitude, exposure to liabilities increase, costs increase, turbulence exposure changes, likelihood of having the system fly in more than one directional strata of winds increases, and the costs of operation changes.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] HAWP systems that are flown must climb through all intermediate altitudes up to final working altitudes—being at first a low- and then a high- altitude device.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] An atlas of the high-altitude wind power resource has been prepared for all points on Earth.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] A similar atlas of global assessment was developed at Joby Energy.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] When a scheme's purpose is to propel ships and boats, the objects tether-placed in the wind will tend to have most of the captured energy be in useful tension in the main tether.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The aloft working bodies will be operated to maintain useful tension even while the ship is moving.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] This is the method for powerkiting sports.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] This sector of HAWP is the most installed method.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Folklore suggests that Benjamin Franklin used the traction method of HAWP.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] George Pocock was a pioneer in tugging vehicles by traction.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Solutions in built systems have control mechanisms variously situated.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems are passive, or active, or a mix.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] When a kite steering unit (KSU) is lofted, the KSU may be robotic and self-contained; a KSU may be operated from the ground via radio-control by a live human operator or by smart computer programs.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems have built sensors in the aircraft body that report parameters like position, relative position to other parts.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Kite control units (KCU) have involved more than steering; tether reeling speeds and directions can be adjusted in response to tether tensions and needs of the system during a power-generating phase or return-non-power-generating phase.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The mechanical energy of the device may be converted to heat, sound, electricity, light, tension, pushes, pulls, laser, microwave, chemical changes, or compression of gases.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Traction is a big direct use of the mechanical energy as in tugging cargo ships and kiteboarders.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] There are several methods of getting the mechanical energy from the wind's kinetic energy.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Lighter-than-air (LTA) moored aerostats are employed as lifters of turbines.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Heavier-than-air (HTA) tethered airfoils are being used as lifters or turbines themselves.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Combinations of LTA and HTA devices in one system are being built and flown to capture HAWP.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Even a family of free-flight airborne devices are represented in the literature that capture the kinetic energy of high-altitude winds (beginning with a description in 1967 by Richard Miller in his book *Without Visible Means of Support*) and a contemporary patent application by Dale C.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Kramer, soaring sailplane competitor, inventor.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] A research on airborne wind turbine technology innovations reveals that the “Kite type AWTs” technique, the most common type, has high scope of growth in the future; it has contributed for about 44% of the total airborne wind energy during 2008–2012.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The kite type AWTs extract energy through wind turbines suspended at high altitudes using kites such as multi-tethered kite, kite and dual purpose circular fan, rotary wing kites etc.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Electricity generation is just one of the options for capturing mechanical energy; however, this option dominates the focus of professionals aiming to supply large amounts of energy to commerce and utilities.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] A long array of secondary options include tugging water turbines, pumping of water, or compressing air or hydrogen.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The position of the electric generator is a distinguishing feature among systems.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Flying the generator aloft is done in a variety of ways.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Keeping the generator at the mooring region is another large design option.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The option in one system of a generator aloft and at the ground station has been used where a small generator operates electronic devices aloft while the ground generator is the big worker to make electricity for significant loads.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The “Carousel” configuration several kites fly at a constant height and higher altitudes, pulling in rotation a generator that moves on a wide circular rail.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] For a large Carousel system, the power obtained can be calculated as of the order of GW, exposing a law that see the power attainable as a function of the diameter raised to the fifth power, while the increment of cost of the generator is linear.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] One method of keeping working HAWP systems aloft is to use buoyant aerostats whether or not the electric generator is lifted or left on the ground.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The aerostats are usually, but not always, shaped to achieve a kiting lifting effect.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Recharging leaked lifting gas receives various solutions.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] In case of productive winds the aerostats are typically blown down by the aerodynamic drag applied on the wide and unavoidable Reynolds surface excluding them de facto from the HAWP category.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Conceptually, two adjacent mountains (natural or terrain-enabled) or artificial buildings or towers (urban or artificial) could have a wind turbine suspended between them by use of cables.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] When HAWP is cabled between two mountain tops across a valley, the HAWP device is not airborne, but borne up by the cable system.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] No such systems are known to be in use, though patents teach these methods.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] When non-cabled bridges are the foundation for holding wind turbines high above the ground, then these are grouped with conventional towered turbines and are outside the intent of HAWP where the tethering an airborne system is foundational.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Lightning, aircraft traffic, emergency procedures, system inspections, visibility marking of system parts and its tethers, electrical safety, runaway-wing procedures, over-powering controls, appropriate mooring, and more form the safety environment for HAWP systems.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] There have been several periods of high interest in HAWP before the contemporary activity.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The first period had a high focus on pulling carriages over the lands and capturing atmospheric electricity and lightning for human use.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The second period was in the 1970s and 1980s when research and investment flourished; a drop in oil price resulted in no significant installations of HAWP.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Return on investment (ROI) has been the key parameter; that ROI remains in focus in the current development activity while in the background is the renewable and sustainable energy movement supporting wind power of any kind; but HAWP must compete on ROI with conventional towered solutions.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] A test center at Lista, Norway provides independent verification of research.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Early centuries of kiting demonstrated that the kite is a rotary engine that rotates its tether part about its mooring point and causes hands and arms to move because of the energy captured from higher winds into the mechanical device.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] The tension in the lofted devices performs the work of lifting and pulling body parts and things.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Airborne wind energy (AWE) for HAWP was birthed thousands of years ago; naming what happened and developing the implied potentials of tethered aircraft for doing special works is what is occurring in AWE HAWP.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] What is "low" for some workers is "high" for others.
[src:energy-transformation/airborne-wind-energy] Autorotation is the basis of a large sector of AWE technology.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:energy-transformation/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Anhydridic bonds are often labelled as "*high-energy bonds"*.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] P-O bonds are in fact fairly strong (~30 kJ/mol stronger than C-N bonds) and themselves not particularly easy to break.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] As noted below, energy is released by the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] However, when the P-O bonds are broken, *input* of energy is required.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] It is the formation of new bonds and lower-energy inorganic phosphate with a *release of a larger amount of energy* that lowers the total energy of the system and makes it more stable.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the phosphate groups in ATP is especially exergonic, because the resulting inorganic phosphate molecular ion is greatly stabilized by multiple resonance structures, making the products (ADP and Pi) lower in energy than the reactant (ATP).
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The high negative charge density associated with the three adjacent phosphate units of ATP also destabilizes the molecule, making it higher in energy.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis relieves some of these electrostatic repulsions, liberating useful energy in the process by causing conformational changes in enzyme structure.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] In humans, approximately 60 percent of the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP produces metabolic heat rather than fuel the actual reactions taking place.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Due to the acid-base properties of ATP, ADP, and inorganic phosphate, the hydrolysis of ATP has the effect of lowering the pH of the reaction medium.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Under certain conditions, high levels of ATP hydrolysis can contribute to lactic acidosis.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the terminal phosphoanhydridic bond is a highly exergonic process.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The amount of released energy depends on the conditions in a particular cell.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Specifically, the energy released is dependent on concentrations of ATP, ADP and Pi.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] As the concentrations of these molecules deviate from values at equilibrium, the value of Gibbs free energy change (Δ*G*) will be increasingly different.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] In standard conditions (ATP, ADP and Pi concentrations are equal to 1M, water concentration is equal to 55 M) the value of Δ*G* is between -28 and -34 kJ/mol.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The range of the Δ*G* value exists because this reaction is dependent on the concentration of Mg2+ cations, which stabilize the ATP molecule.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The cellular environment also contributes to differences in the Δ*G* value since ATP hydrolysis is dependent not only on the studied cell, but also on the surrounding tissue and even the compartment within the cell.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Variability in the Δ*G* values is therefore to be expected.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The relationship between the standard Gibbs free energy change Δr*G*o and chemical equilibrium is revealing.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] This relationship is defined by the equation Δr*G*o = -*RT* ln(*K*), where *K* is the equilibrium constant, which is equal to the reaction quotient *Q* in equilibrium.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The standard value of Δ*G* for this reaction is, as mentioned, between -28 and -34 kJ/mol; however, experimentally determined concentrations of the involved molecules reveal that the reaction is not at equilibrium.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Given this fact, a comparison between the equilibrium constant, *K*, and the reaction quotient, *Q*, provides insight.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] *K* takes into consideration reactions taking place in standard conditions, but in the cellular environment the concentrations of the involved molecules (namely, ATP, ADP, and Pi) are far from the standard 1 M.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] In fact, the concentrations are more appropriately measured in mM, which is smaller than M by three orders of magnitude.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Using these nonstandard concentrations, the calculated value of *Q* is much less than one.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] By relating *Q* to Δ*G* using the equation Δ*G* = Δr*G*o + *RT* ln(*Q*), where Δr*G*o is the standard change in Gibbs free energy for the hydrolysis of ATP, it is found that the magnitude of Δ*G* is much greater than the standard value.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] The nonstandard conditions of the cell actually result in a more favorable reaction.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] In one particular study, to determine Δ*G* in vivo in humans, the concentration of ATP, ADP, and Pi was measured using nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] In human muscle cells at rest, the concentration of ATP was found to be around 4 mM and the concentration of ADP was around 9 μM.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Inputing these values into the above equations yields Δ*G* = -64 kJ/mol.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] After ischemia, when the muscle is recovering from exercise, the concentration of ATP is as low as 1 mM and the concentration of ADP is around 7 μM.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] Therefore, the absolute Δ*G* would be as high as -69 kJ/mol.
[src:energy-transformation/atp-hydrolysis] By comparing the standard value of Δ*G* and the experimental value of Δ*G*, one can see that the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP, as measured in humans, is almost twice as much as the energy produced under standard conditions.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:energy-transformation/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] An **avalanche** is a rapid flow of snow down a slope, such as a hill or mountain.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches can be triggered spontaneously, by factors such as increased precipitation or snowpack weakening, or by external means such as humans, other animals, and earthquakes.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Primarily composed of flowing snow and air, large avalanches have the capability to capture and move ice, rocks, and trees.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches occur in two general forms, or combinations thereof: **slab avalanches** made of tightly packed snow, triggered by a collapse of an underlying weak snow layer, and **loose snow avalanches** made of looser snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] After being set off, avalanches usually accelerate rapidly and grow in mass and volume as they capture more snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] If an avalanche moves fast enough, some of the snow may mix with the air, forming a powder snow avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Though they appear to share similarities, avalanches are distinct from slush flows, mudslides, rock slides, and serac collapses.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They are also different from large scale movements of ice.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches can happen in any mountain range that has an enduring snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They are most frequent in winter or spring, but may occur at any time of the year.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In mountainous areas, avalanches are among the most serious natural hazards to life and property, so great efforts are made in avalanche control.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] There are many classification systems for the different forms of avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches can be described by their size, destructive potential, initiation mechanism, composition, and dynamics.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Most avalanches occur spontaneously during storms under increased load due to snowfall and/or erosion.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Metamorphic changes in the snowpack, such as melting due to solar radiation, is the second-largest cause of natural avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Other natural causes include rain, earthquakes, rockfall, and icefall.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Artificial triggers of avalanches include skiers, snowmobiles, and controlled explosive work.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Contrary to popular belief, avalanches are not triggered by loud sound; the pressure from sound is orders of magnitude too small to trigger an avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanche initiation can start at a point with only a small amount of snow moving initially; this is typical of wet snow avalanches or avalanches in dry unconsolidated snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] However, if the snow has sintered into a stiff slab overlying a weak layer, then fractures can propagate very rapidly, so that a large volume of snow, possibly thousands of cubic metres, can start moving almost simultaneously.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A snowpack will fail when the load exceeds the strength.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The load is straightforward; it is the weight of the snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] However, the strength of the snowpack is much more difficult to determine and is extremely heterogeneous.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] It varies in detail with properties of the snow grains, size, density, morphology, temperature, water content; and the properties of the bonds between the grains.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These properties may all metamorphose in time according to the local humidity, water vapour flux, temperature and heat flux.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The top of the snowpack is also extensively influenced by incoming radiation and the local air flow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] One of the aims of avalanche research is to develop and validate computer models that can describe the evolution of the seasonal snowpack over time.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A complicating factor is the complex interaction of terrain and weather, which causes significant spatial and temporal variability of the depths, crystal forms, and layering of the seasonal snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slab avalanches are formed frequently in snow that has been deposited, or deposited by wind.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They have the characteristic appearance of a block (slab) of snow cut out from its surroundings by fractures.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Elements of slab avalanches include a crown fracture at the top of the start zone, flank fractures on the sides of the start zones, and a fracture at the bottom called the stauchwall.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The crown and flank fractures are vertical walls in the snow delineating the snow that was entrained in the avalanche from the snow that remained on the slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slabs can vary in thickness from a few centimetres to three metres.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slab avalanches account for around 90% of avalanche-related fatalities.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The largest avalanches form turbulent suspension currents known as powder snow avalanches or mixed avalanches, a kind of gravity current.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These consist of a powder cloud, which overlies a dense avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They can form from any type of snow or initiation mechanism, but usually occur with fresh dry powder.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They can exceed speeds of 300 km/h (190 mph), and masses of 1,000,000 tons; their flows can travel long distances along flat valley bottoms and even uphill for short distances.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In contrast to powder snow avalanches, wet snow avalanches are a low velocity suspension of snow and water, with the flow confined to the track surface (McClung, 1999, p.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The low speed of travel is due to the friction between the sliding surface of the track and the water saturated flow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Despite the low speed of travel (≈10–40 km/h), wet snow avalanches are capable of generating powerful destructive forces, due to the large mass and density.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The body of the flow of a wet snow avalanche can plough through soft snow, and can scour boulders, earth, trees, and other vegetation; leaving exposed and often scored ground in the avalanche track.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Wet snow avalanches can be initiated from either loose snow releases, or slab releases, and only occur in snowpacks that are water saturated and isothermally equilibrated to the melting point of water.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The isothermal characteristic of wet snow avalanches has led to the secondary term of isothermal slides found in the literature (for example in Daffern, 1999, p.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] At temperate latitudes wet snow avalanches are frequently associated with climatic avalanche cycles at the end of the winter season, when there is significant daytime warming.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] An ice avalanche occurs when a large piece of ice, such as from a serac or calving glacier, falls onto ice (such as the Khumbu Icefall), triggering a movement of broken ice chunks.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The resulting movement is more analogous to a rockfall or a landslide than a snow avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They are typically very difficult to predict and almost impossible to mitigate.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] As an avalanche moves down a slope it follows a certain pathway that is dependent on the slope's degree of steepness and the volume of snow/ice involved in the mass movement.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The origin of an avalanche is called the Starting Point and typically occurs on a 30–45 degree slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The body of the pathway is called the Track of the avalanche and usually occurs on a 20–30 degree slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When the avalanche loses its momentum and eventually stops it reaches the Runout Zone.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This usually occurs when the slope has reached a steepness that is less than 20 degrees.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These degrees are not consistently true due to the fact that each avalanche is unique depending on the stability of the snowpack that it was derived from as well as the environmental or human influences that triggered the mass movement.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] People caught in avalanches can die from suffocation, trauma, or hypothermia.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] From "1950–1951 to 2020–2021" there were 1,169 people who died in avalanches in the United States.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] For the 11-year period ending April 2006, 445 people died in avalanches throughout North America.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] On average, 28 people die in avalanches every winter in the United States.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In 2001 it was reported that globally an average of 150 people die each year from avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Doug Fesler and Jill Fredston developed a conceptual model of the three primary elements of avalanches: terrain, weather, and snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Terrain describes the places where avalanches occur, weather describes the meteorological conditions that create the snowpack, and snowpack describes the structural characteristics of snow that make avalanche formation possible.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanche formation requires a slope shallow enough for snow to accumulate but steep enough for the snow to accelerate once set in motion by the combination of mechanical failure (of the snowpack) and gravity.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The angle of the slope that can hold snow, called the angle of repose, depends on a variety of factors, such as crystal form and moisture content.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Some forms of drier and colder snow will only stick to shallower slopes, while wet and warm snow can bond to very steep surfaces.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In coastal mountains, such as the Cordillera del Paine region of Patagonia, deep snowpacks collect on vertical and even overhanging rock faces.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The slope angle that can allow moving snow to accelerate depends on a variety of factors such as the snow's shear strength (which is itself dependent upon crystal form) and the configuration of layers and inter-layer interfaces.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The snowpack on slopes with sunny exposures is strongly influenced by sunshine.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Diurnal cycles of thawing and refreezing can stabilize the snowpack by promoting settlement.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Strong freeze-thaw cycles result in the formation of surface crusts during the night and of unstable surface snow during the day.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slopes in the lee of a ridge or of another wind obstacle accumulate more snow and are more likely to include pockets of deep snow, wind slabs, and cornices, all of which, when disturbed, may result in avalanche formation.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Conversely, the snowpack on a windward slope is often much shallower than on a lee slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches and avalanche paths share common elements: a start zone where the avalanche originates, a track along which the avalanche flows, and a runout zone where the avalanche comes to rest.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The debris deposit is the accumulated mass of the avalanched snow once it has come to rest in the run-out zone.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] For the image at left, many small avalanches form in this avalanche path every year, but most of these avalanches do not run the full vertical or horizontal length of the path.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The frequency with which avalanches form in a given area is known as the return period.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The start zone of an avalanche must be steep enough to allow snow to accelerate once set in motion, additionally convex slopes are less stable than concave slopes because of the disparity between the tensile strength of snow layers and their compressive strength.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The composition and structure of the ground surface beneath the snowpack influences the stability of the snowpack, either being a source of strength or weakness.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches are unlikely to form in very thick forests, but boulders and sparsely distributed vegetation can create weak areas deep within the snowpack through the formation of strong temperature gradients.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Full-depth avalanches (avalanches that sweep a slope virtually clean of snow cover) are more common on slopes with smooth ground, such as grass or rock slabs.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Generally speaking, avalanches follow drainages down-slope, frequently sharing drainage features with summertime watersheds.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] At and below tree line, avalanche paths through drainages are well defined by vegetation boundaries called trim lines, which occur where avalanches have removed trees and prevented regrowth of large vegetation.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Engineered drainages, such as the avalanche dam on Mount Stephen in Kicking Horse Pass, have been constructed to protect people and property by redirecting the flow of avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Deep debris deposits from avalanches will collect in catchments at the terminus of a run out, such as gullies and river beds.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slopes flatter than 25 degrees or steeper than 60 degrees typically have a lower incidence of avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Human-triggered avalanches have the greatest incidence when the snow's angle of repose is between 35 and 45 degrees; the critical angle, the angle at which human-triggered avalanches are most frequent, is 38 degrees.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When the incidence of human triggered avalanches is normalized by the rates of recreational use, however, hazard increases uniformly with slope angle, and no significant difference in hazard for a given exposure direction can be found.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The snowpack is composed of ground-parallel layers that accumulate over the winter.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Each layer contains ice grains that are representative of the distinct meteorological conditions during which the snow formed and was deposited.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Once deposited, a snow layer continues to evolve under the influence of the meteorological conditions that prevail after deposition.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] For an avalanche to occur, it is necessary that a snowpack have a weak layer (or instability) below a slab of cohesive snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Second, the relationship between readily observable snowpack characteristics and the snowpack's critical mechanical properties has not been completely developed.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] While the deterministic relationship between snowpack characteristics and snowpack stability is still a matter of ongoing scientific study, there is a growing empirical understanding of the snow composition and deposition characteristics that influence the likelihood of an avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Observation and experience has shown that newly fallen snow requires time to bond with the snow layers beneath it, especially if the new snow falls during very cold and dry conditions.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] If ambient air temperatures are cold enough, shallow snow above or around boulders, plants, and other discontinuities in the slope, weakens from rapid crystal growth that occurs in the presence of a critical temperature gradient.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Large, angular snow crystals are indicators of weak snow, because such crystals have fewer bonds per unit volume than small, rounded crystals that pack tightly together.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Consolidated snow is less likely to slough than loose powdery layers or wet isothermal snow; however, consolidated snow is a necessary condition for the occurrence of slab avalanches, and persistent instabilities within the snowpack can hide below well-consolidated surface layers.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Uncertainty associated with the empirical understanding of the factors influencing snow stability leads most professional avalanche workers to recommend conservative use of avalanche terrain relative to current snowpack instability.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanches only occur in a standing snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Typically winter seasons at high latitudes, high altitudes, or both have weather that is sufficiently unsettled and cold enough for precipitated snow to accumulate into a seasonal snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Continentality, through its potentiating influence on the meteorological extremes experienced by snowpacks, is an important factor in the evolution of instabilities, and consequential occurrence of avalanches faster stabilization of the snowpack after storm cycles.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The evolution of the snowpack is critically sensitive to small variations within the narrow range of meteorological conditions that allow for the accumulation of snow into a snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Among the critical factors controlling snowpack evolution are: heating by the sun, radiational cooling, vertical temperature gradients in standing snow, snowfall amounts, and snow types.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Generally, mild winter weather will promote the settlement and stabilization of the snowpack; conversely, very cold, windy, or hot weather will weaken the snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] At temperatures close to the freezing point of water, or during times of moderate solar radiation, a gentle freeze-thaw cycle will take place.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The melting and refreezing of water in the snow strengthens the snowpack during the freezing phase and weakens it during the thawing phase.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A rapid rise in temperature, to a point significantly above the freezing point of water, may cause avalanche formation at any time of year.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Persistent cold temperatures can either prevent new snow from stabilizing or destabilize the existing snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Cold air temperatures on the snow surface produce a temperature gradient in the snow, because the ground temperature at the base of the snowpack is usually around 0 °C, and the ambient air temperature can be much colder.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When a temperature gradient greater than 10 °C change per vertical meter of snow is sustained for more than a day, angular crystals called depth hoar or facets begin forming in the snowpack because of rapid moisture transport along the temperature gradient.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These angular crystals, which bond poorly to one another and the surrounding snow, often become a persistent weakness in the snowpack.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When a slab lying on top of a persistent weakness is loaded by a force greater than the strength of the slab and persistent weak layer, the persistent weak layer can fail and generate an avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Any wind stronger than a light breeze can contribute to a rapid accumulation of snow on sheltered slopes downwind.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Wind slabs form quickly and, if present, weaker snow below the slab may not have time to adjust to the new load.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Even on a clear day, wind can quickly load a slope with snow by blowing snow from one place to another.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Top-loading occurs when wind deposits snow from the top of a slope; cross-loading occurs when wind deposits snow parallel to the slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When a wind blows over the top of a mountain, the leeward, or downwind, side of the mountain experiences top-loading, from the top to the bottom of that lee slope.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When the wind blows across a ridge that leads up the mountain, the leeward side of the ridge is subject to cross-loading.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Cross-loaded wind-slabs are usually difficult to identify visually.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Snowstorms and rainstorms are important contributors to avalanche danger.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Heavy snowfall will cause instability in the existing snowpack, both because of the additional weight and because the new snow has insufficient time to bond to underlying snow layers.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In the short term, rain causes instability because, like a heavy snowfall, it imposes an additional load on the snowpack and once rainwater seeps down through the snow, acts as a lubricant, reducing the natural friction between snow layers that holds the snowpack together.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Most avalanches happen during or soon after a storm.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Daytime exposure to sunlight will rapidly destabilize the upper layers of the snowpack if the sunlight is strong enough to melt the snow, thereby reducing its hardness.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] During clear nights, the snowpack can re-freeze when ambient air temperatures fall below freezing, through the process of long-wave radiative cooling, or both.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Radiative heat loss occurs when the night air is significantly cooler than the snowpack, and the heat stored in the snow is re-radiated into the atmosphere.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When a slab avalanche forms, the slab disintegrates into increasingly smaller fragments as the snow travels downhill.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] If the fragments become small enough the outer layer of the avalanche, called a saltation layer, takes on the characteristics of a fluid.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When sufficiently fine particles are present they can become airborne and, given a sufficient quantity of airborne snow, this portion of the avalanche can become separated from the bulk of the avalanche and travel a greater distance as a powder snow avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Scientific studies using radar, following the 1999 Galtür avalanche disaster, confirmed the hypothesis that a saltation layer forms between the surface and the airborne components of an avalanche, which can also separate from the bulk of the avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Driving an avalanche is the component of the avalanche's weight parallel to the slope; as the avalanche progresses any unstable snow in its path will tend to become incorporated, so increasing the overall weight.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This force will increase as the steepness of the slope increases, and diminish as the slope flattens.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] An avalanche will continue to accelerate until the resistance exceeds the forward force.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Attempts to model avalanche behaviour date from the early 20th century, notably the work of Professor Lagotala in preparation for the 1924 Winter Olympics in Chamonix.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Voellmy and popularised following the publication in 1955 of his *Ueber die Zerstörungskraft von Lawinen* (On the Destructive Force of Avalanches).
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] He and others subsequently derived other formulae that take other factors into account, with the Voellmy-Salm-Gubler and the Perla-Cheng-McClung models becoming most widely used as simple tools to model flowing (as opposed to powder snow) avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Since the 1990s many more sophisticated models have been developed.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Other known models are the SAMOS-AT avalanche simulation software and the RAMMS software.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Preventative measures are employed in areas where avalanches pose a significant threat to people, such as ski resorts, mountain towns, roads, and railways.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] There are several ways to prevent avalanches and lessen their power and develop preventative measures to reduce the likelihood and size of avalanches by disrupting the structure of the snowpack, while passive measures reinforce and stabilize the snowpack *in situ*.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The simplest active measure is repeatedly traveling on a snowpack as snow accumulates; this can be by means of boot-packing, ski-cutting, or machine grooming.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Explosives are used extensively to prevent avalanches, by triggering smaller avalanches that break down instabilities in the snowpack, and removing overburden that can result in larger avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Explosive charges are delivered by a number of methods including hand-tossed charges, helicopter-dropped bombs, Gazex concussion lines, and ballistic projectiles launched by air cannons and artillery.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Passive preventive systems such as snow fences and light walls can be used to direct the placement of snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Snow builds up around the fence, especially the side that faces the prevailing winds.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Downwind of the fence, snow build-up is lessened.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This is caused by the loss of snow at the fence that would have been deposited and the pickup of the snow that is already there by the wind, which was depleted of snow at the fence.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] When there is a sufficient density of trees, they can greatly reduce the strength of avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They hold snow in place and when there is an avalanche, the impact of the snow against the trees slows it down.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Trees can either be planted or they can be conserved, such as in the building of a ski resort, to reduce the strength of avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In many areas, regular avalanche tracks can be identified and precautions can be taken to minimize damage, such as the prevention of development in these areas.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] To mitigate the effect of avalanches the construction of artificial barriers can be very effective in reducing avalanche damage.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] There are several types: One kind of barrier (snow net) uses a net strung between poles that are anchored by guy wires in addition to their foundations.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These barriers are similar to those used for rockslides.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Another type of barrier is a rigid fence-like structure (snow fence) and may be constructed of steel, wood or pre-stressed concrete.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They usually have gaps between the beams and are built perpendicular to the slope, with reinforcing beams on the downhill side.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Rigid barriers are often considered unsightly, especially when many rows must be built.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They are also expensive and vulnerable to damage from falling rocks in the warmer months.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In addition to industrially manufactured barriers, landscaped barriers, called avalanche dams stop or deflect avalanches with their weight and strength.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] These barriers are made out of concrete, rocks, or earth.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] They are usually placed right above the structure, road, or railway that they are trying to protect, although they can also be used to channel avalanches into other barriers.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Occasionally, earth mounds are placed in the avalanche's path to slow it down.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Finally, along transportation corridors, large shelters, called snow sheds, can be built directly in the slide path of an avalanche to protect traffic from avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Warning systems can detect avalanches which develop slowly, such as ice avalanches caused by icefalls from glaciers.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Interferometric radars, high-resolution cameras, or motion sensors can monitor unstable areas over a long term, lasting from days to years.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Experts interpret the recorded data and are able to recognize upcoming ruptures in order to initiate appropriate measures.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Such systems (e.g. the monitoring of the Weissmies glacier in Switzerland) can recognize events several days in advance.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Modern radar technology enables the monitoring of large areas and the localization of avalanches at any weather condition, by day and by night.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Complex alarm systems are able to detect avalanches within a short time in order to close (e.g. roads and rails) or evacuate (e.g. construction sites) endangered areas.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] An example of such a system is installed on the only access road of Zermatt in Switzerland.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Two radars monitor the slope of a mountain above the road.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The system automatically closes the road by activating several barriers and traffic lights within seconds such that no people are harmed.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanche accidents are broadly differentiated into 2 categories: accidents in recreational settings, and accidents in residential, industrial, and transportation settings.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This distinction is motivated by the observed difference in the causes of avalanche accidents in the two settings.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In the recreational setting most accidents are caused by the people involved in the avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] (pages 7–20) found that 83% of all avalanches in the recreational setting were caused by those who were involved in the accident.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In contrast, all the accidents in the residential, industrial, and transportation settings were due to spontaneous natural avalanches.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Because of the difference in the causes of avalanche accidents, and the activities pursued in the two settings, avalanche and disaster management professionals have developed two related preparedness, rescue, and recovery strategies for each of the settings.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Two avalanches occurred in March 1910 in the Cascade and Selkirk Mountain ranges.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] On 1 March the Wellington avalanche killed 96 in Washington state, United States.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Three days later 62 railroad workers were killed in the Rogers Pass avalanche in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] During World War I, an estimated 40,000 to 80,000 soldiers died as a result of avalanches during the mountain campaign in the Alps at the Austrian-Italian front, many of which were caused by artillery fire.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Some 10,000 men, from both sides, died in avalanches in December 1916.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In the Northern Hemisphere winter of 1950–1951 approximately 649 avalanches were recorded in a three-month period throughout the Alps in Austria, France, Switzerland, Italy and Germany.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This series of avalanches killed around 265 people and was termed the Winter of Terror.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The avalanche in Biały Jar occurred on 20 March 1968, sweeping away 24 people who were walking along the bottom of Biały Jar ravine in the Giant Mountains.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Five of them, who were thrown aside by the avalanche, would survive.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The remaining 19 people – including 13 Russians, 4 citizens of East Germany, and two Polish citizens – were killed.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A total of 1,100 people took part in the rescue operation.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A mountain climbing camp on Lenin Peak, in what is now Kyrgyzstan, was wiped out in 1990 when an earthquake triggered a large avalanche that overran the camp.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In 1993, the Bayburt Üzengili avalanche killed 60 individuals in Üzengili in the province of Bayburt, Turkey.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A large avalanche in Montroc, France, in 1999, 300,000 cubic metres of snow slid on a 30° slope, achieving a speed in the region of 100 km/h (62 mph).
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] It killed 12 people in their chalets under 100,000 tons of snow, 5 meters (16 feet) deep.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The mayor of Chamonix was convicted of second-degree murder for not evacuating the area, but received a suspended sentence.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The small Austrian village of Galtür was hit by the Galtür avalanche in 1999.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The village was thought to be in a safe zone but the avalanche was exceptionally large and flowed into the village.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] On 28 January 2003, the Tatra Mountains avalanche swept away nine out of a thirteen-member group heading to the summit of Rysy in the Tatra Mountains.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The participants of the trip were students from the I Leon Kruczkowski High School in Tychy and individuals associated with the school's sports club.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] On 3 July 2022 a serac collapsed on the Marmolada Glacier, Italy, causing an avalanche that killed 11 alpinists and injured eight.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In Europe, the avalanche risk is widely rated on the following scale, which was adopted in April 1993 to replace the earlier non-standard national schemes.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Descriptions were last updated in May 2003 to enhance uniformity.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In France, most avalanche deaths occur at risk levels 3 and 4.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In Switzerland most occur at levels 2 and 3.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] It is thought that this may be due to national differences of interpretation when assessing the risks.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In the United States and Canada, the following avalanche danger scale is used.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The Canadian classification for avalanche size is based upon the consequences of the avalanche.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The size of avalanches are classified using two scales; size relative to destructive force or D-scale and size relative to the avalanche path or R-scale.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] With the D-scale, half sizes can be used.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Slab avalanche hazard analysis can be done using the Rutschblock Test.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] A 2 m wide block of snow is isolated from the rest of the slope and progressively loaded.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The result is a rating of slope stability on a seven step scale.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Avalanche formation and frequency is highly affected by weather patterns and the local climate.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Snowpack layers will form differently depending on whether snow is falling in very cold or very warm conditions, and very dry or very humid conditions.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Thus, climate change may affect when, where, and how often avalanches occur, and may also change the type of avalanches that are occurring.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Overall, a rising seasonal snow line and a decrease in the number of days with snow cover are predicted.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Climate change-caused temperature increases and changes in precipitation patterns will likely differ between the different mountain regions, and the impacts of these changes on avalanches will change at different elevations.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] In the long term, avalanche frequency at lower elevations is expected to decline corresponding to a decrease in snow cover and depth, and a short-term increase in the number of wet avalanches are predicted.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Precipitation is expected to increase, meaning more snow or rain depending on the elevation.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Higher elevations predicted to remain above the seasonal snow line will likely see an increase in avalanche activity due to the increases in precipitation during the winter season.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Storm precipitation intensity is also expected to increase, which is likely to lead to more days with enough snowfall to cause the snowpack to become unstable.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Moderate and high elevations may see an increase in volatile swings from one weather extreme to the other.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Predictions also show an increase in the number of rain on snow events, and wet avalanche cycles occurring earlier in the spring during the remainder of this century.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] The warm, wet snowpacks that are likely to increase in frequency due to climate change may also make avalanche burials more deadly.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Warm snow has a higher moisture content and is therefore denser than colder snow.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Denser avalanche debris decreases the ability for a buried person to breathe and the amount of time they have before they run out of oxygen.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] This increases the likelihood of death by asphyxia in the event of a burial.
[src:energy-transformation/avalanches] Additionally, the predicted thinner snowpacks may increase the frequency of injuries due to trauma, such as a buried skier striking a rock or tree.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Older children do not have problems with batteries smaller than 21–23 mm.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Liquefaction necrosis may occur because sodium hydroxide is generated by the current produced by the battery (usually at the anode).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Perforation has occurred as rapidly as 6 hours after ingestion.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Some manufacturers add a bittering agent to their batteries to discourage swallowing.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] Legislation around electric batteries includes such topics as safe disposal and recycling.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In response to reported accidents and failures, occasionally ignition or explosion, recalls of devices using lithium-ion batteries have become more common in recent years.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In the United States, the Mercury-Containing and Rechargeable Battery Management Act of 1996 banned the sale of mercury-containing batteries, enacted uniform labeling requirements for rechargeable batteries and required that rechargeable batteries be easily removable.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] California and New York City prohibit the disposal of rechargeable batteries in solid waste.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The rechargeable battery industry operates nationwide recycling programs in the United States and Canada, with dropoff points at local retailers.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] The Battery Directive of the European Union has similar requirements, in addition to requiring increased recycling of batteries and promoting research on improved battery recycling methods.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] In accordance with this directive all batteries to be sold within the EU must be marked with the "collection symbol" (a crossed-out wheeled bin).
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] This must cover at least 3% of the surface of prismatic batteries and 1.5% of the surface of cylindrical batteries.
[src:energy-transformation/battery-electricity] On 9 December 2022, the European Parliament reached an agreement to force, from 2026, manufacturers to design all electrical appliances sold in the EU (and not used predominantly in wet conditions) so that consumers can easily remove and replace batteries themselves.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The **Big Bang** is a physical theory that describes how the universe expanded from an initial state of high density and temperature.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Various cosmological models based on the Big Bang concept explain a broad range of phenomena, including the abundance of light elements, the cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation, the redshift of galaxies and the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The observed uniformity of the universe, which leads to the horizon and flatness problems, is explained through cosmic inflation: a phase of accelerated expansion during the earliest stages.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Detailed measurements of the expansion rate of the universe place the initial singularity at an estimated 13.787±0.02 billion years ago, which is considered the age of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A wide range of empirical evidence strongly favors the Big Bang event, which is now widely accepted.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Extrapolating this cosmic expansion backward in time using the known laws of physics, the models describe an extraordinarily hot and dense primordial universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Physics lacks a widely accepted theory that can model the earliest conditions of the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] As the universe expanded, it cooled sufficiently to allow the formation of subatomic particles, and later atoms.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These primordial elements—mostly hydrogen, with some helium and lithium—then coalesced under the force of gravity aided by dark matter, forming early stars and galaxies.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the redshifts of supernovae indicate that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, an observation attributed to a concept called dark energy.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The concept of an expanding universe was introduced by the physicist Alexander Friedmann in 1922 with the mathematical derivation of the Friedmann equations.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The earliest empirical observation of an expanding universe is known as Hubble's law, published in work by physicist Edwin Hubble in 1929, which discerned that galaxies are moving away from Earth at a rate that accelerates proportionally with distance.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Independent of Friedmann's work, and independent of Hubble's observations, in 1931 physicist Georges Lemaître proposed that the universe emerged from a "primeval atom", introducing the modern notion of the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1964, the CMB was accidentally discovered.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Over the next few years measurements showed this radiation to be uniform over directions in the sky and the shape of the energy versus intensity curve, both consistent with the Big Bang models of high temperatures and densities in the distant past.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] By the late 1960s most cosmologists were convinced that competing steady-state model of cosmic evolution was incorrect.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] There remain aspects of the observed universe that are not yet adequately explained by the Big Bang models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These include the unequal abundances of matter and antimatter known as baryon asymmetry, the detailed nature of dark matter surrounding galaxies, and the origin of dark energy.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Big Bang cosmology models depend on three major assumptions: the universality of physical laws, the cosmological principle, and that the matter content can be modeled as a perfect fluid.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The universality of physical laws is one of the underlying principles of the theory of relativity.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle states that on large scales the universe is homogeneous and isotropic—appearing the same in all directions regardless of location.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A perfect fluid has no viscosity; the pressure of a perfect fluid is proportional to its density.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These ideas were initially taken as postulates, but later efforts were made to test each of them.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For example, the first assumption has been tested by observations showing that the largest possible deviation of the fine-structure constant over much of the age of the universe is of order 10−5.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The key physical law behind these models, general relativity has passed stringent tests on the scale of the Solar System and binary stars.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle has been confirmed to a level of 10−5 via observations of the temperature of the CMB.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At the scale of the CMB horizon, the universe has been measured to be homogeneous with an upper bound on the order of 10% inhomogeneity, as of 1995.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle dramatically simplifies the equations of general relativity, giving the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker metric to describe the geometry of the universe and, with the assumption of a perfect fluid, the Friedmann equations giving the time dependence of that geometry.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The only parameter at this level of description is the mass-energy density: the geometry of the universe and its expansion is a direct consequence of its density.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] All of the major features of Big Bang cosmology are related to these results.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In Big Bang cosmology, the mass–energy density controls the shape and evolution of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] By combining astronomical observations with known laws of thermodynamics and particle physics, cosmologists have worked out the components of the density over the lifespan of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In the current universe, luminous matter, the stars, planets, and so on makes up less than 5% of the density.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Dark matter accounts for 27% and dark energy the remaining 68%.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] An important feature of the Big Bang spacetime is the presence of particle horizons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Since the universe has a finite age, and light travels at a finite speed, there may be events in the past whose light has not yet had time to reach earth.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This places a limit or a *past horizon* on the most distant objects that can be observed.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Conversely, because space is expanding, and more distant objects are receding ever more quickly, light emitted by us today may never "catch up" to very distant objects.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This defines a *future horizon*, which limits the events in the future that we will be able to influence.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The presence of either type of horizon depends on the details of the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker (FLRW) metric that describes the expansion of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Our understanding of the universe back to very early times suggests that there is a past horizon, though in practice our view is also limited by the opacity of the universe at early times.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] So our view cannot extend further backward in time, though the horizon recedes in space.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] If the expansion of the universe continues to accelerate, there is a future horizon as well.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Some processes in the early universe occurred too slowly, compared to the expansion rate of the universe, to reach approximate thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Others were fast enough to reach thermalization.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The parameter usually used to find out whether a process in the very early universe has reached thermal equilibrium is the ratio between the rate of the process (usually rate of collisions between particles) and the Hubble parameter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The larger the ratio, the more time particles had to thermalize before they were too far away from each other.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] According to the Big Bang models, the universe at the beginning was very hot and very compact, and since then it has been expanding and cooling.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Existing theories of physics cannot tell us about the moment of the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Extrapolation of the expansion of the universe backwards in time using only classical general relativity yields a gravitational singularity with infinite density and temperature at a finite time in the past.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] However this classical gravitational theory is expected to be inadequate to describe physics under these conditions.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Thus the meaning of this singularity in the context of the Big Bang is unclear.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The earliest time that general relativity can be applied is called the Planck time.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Earlier, during the Planck epoch, when the temperature of the universe was close to the Planck scale (around 1032 K or 1028 eV) quantum gravity effects are expected to be dominant.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] To date there is no accepted theory of quantum gravity; above the Planck energy scale, undiscovered physics could influence the expansion history of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The earliest phases of the Big Bang are subject to much speculation, given the lack of available data.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In the most common models the universe was filled homogeneously and isotropically with a very high energy density and huge temperatures and pressures, and was very rapidly expanding and cooling.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The period up to 10−43 seconds into the expansion, the Planck epoch, was a phase in which the four fundamental forces—the electromagnetic force, the strong nuclear force, the weak nuclear force, and the gravitational force—were unified as one.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In this stage, the characteristic scale length of the universe was the Planck length, 1.6×10−35 m, and consequently had a temperature of approximately 1032 degrees Celsius.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Even the very concept of a particle breaks down in these conditions.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A proper understanding of this period awaits the development of a theory of quantum gravity.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The Planck epoch was succeeded by the grand unification epoch beginning at 10−43 seconds, where gravitation separated from the other forces as the universe's temperature fell.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At approximately 10−37 seconds into the expansion, a phase transition caused a cosmic inflation, during which the universe grew exponentially, unconstrained by the light speed invariance, and temperatures dropped by a factor of 100,000.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This concept is motivated by the flatness problem, where the density of matter and energy is very close to the critical density needed to produce a flat universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] That is, the shape of the universe has no overall geometric curvature due to gravitational influence.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Microscopic quantum fluctuations that occurred because of Heisenberg's uncertainty principle were "frozen in" by inflation, becoming amplified into the seeds that would later form the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At a time around 10−36 seconds, the electroweak epoch begins when the strong nuclear force separates from the other forces, with only the electromagnetic force and weak nuclear force remaining unified.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] All of the mass-energy in all of the galaxies currently visible started in a sphere with a radius around 4 × 10−29 m then grew to a sphere with a radius around 0.9 m by the end of inflation.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Reheating followed as the inflaton field decayed, until the universe obtained the temperatures required for the production of a quark–gluon plasma as well as all other elementary particles.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Temperatures were so high that the random motions of particles were at relativistic speeds, and particle–antiparticle pairs of all kinds were being continuously created and destroyed in collisions.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At some point, an unknown reaction called baryogenesis violated the conservation of baryon number, leading to a very small excess of quarks and leptons over antiquarks and antileptons—of the order of one part in 30 million.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This resulted in the predominance of matter over antimatter in the present universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The universe continued to decrease in density and fall in temperature, hence the typical energy of each particle was decreasing.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Symmetry-breaking phase transitions put the fundamental forces of physics and the parameters of elementary particles into their present form, with the electromagnetic force and weak nuclear force separating at about 10−12 seconds.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] After about 10−11 seconds, the picture becomes less speculative, since particle energies drop to values that can be attained in particle accelerators.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At about 10−6 seconds, quarks and gluons combined to form baryons such as protons and neutrons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The small excess of quarks over antiquarks led to a small excess of baryons over antibaryons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The temperature was no longer high enough to create either new proton–antiproton or neutron–antineutron pairs.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A mass annihilation immediately followed, leaving just one in 108 of the original matter particles and none of their antiparticles.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A similar process happened at about 1 second for electrons and positrons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] After these annihilations, the remaining protons, neutrons and electrons were no longer moving relativistically and the energy density of the universe was dominated by photons (with a minor contribution from neutrinos).
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Most protons remained uncombined as hydrogen nuclei.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] As the universe cooled, the rest energy density of matter came to gravitationally dominate over that of the photon and neutrino radiation at a time of about 50,000 years.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] At a time of about 380,000 years, the universe cooled enough that electrons and nuclei combined into neutral atoms (mostly hydrogen) in an event called recombination.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This process made the previously opaque universe transparent, and the photons that last scattered during this epoch comprise the cosmic microwave background.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] After the recombination epoch, the slightly denser regions of the uniformly distributed matter gravitationally attracted nearby matter and thus grew even denser, forming gas clouds, stars, galaxies, and the other astronomical structures observable today.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The details of this process depend on the amount and type of matter in the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The four possible types of matter are known as cold dark matter (CDM), warm dark matter, hot dark matter, and baryonic matter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The best measurements available, from the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe (WMAP), show that the data is well-fit by a Lambda-CDM model in which dark matter is assumed to be cold.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This CDM is estimated to make up about 23% of the matter/energy of the universe, while baryonic matter makes up about 4.6%.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Independent lines of evidence from Type Ia supernovae and the CMB imply that the universe today is dominated by a mysterious form of energy known as dark energy, which appears to homogeneously permeate all of space.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Observations suggest that 73% of the total energy density of the present day universe is in this form.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] When the universe was very young it was likely infused with dark energy, but with everything closer together, gravity predominated, braking the expansion.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Eventually, after billions of years of expansion, the declining density of matter relative to the density of dark energy allowed the expansion of the universe to begin to accelerate.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Dark energy in its simplest formulation is modeled by a cosmological constant term in Einstein field equations of general relativity, but its composition and mechanism are unknown.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] More generally, the details of its equation of state and relationship with the Standard Model of particle physics continue to be investigated both through observation and theory.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] All of this cosmic evolution after the inflationary epoch can be rigorously described and modeled by the lambda-CDM model of cosmology, which uses the independent frameworks of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] There are no easily testable models that would describe the situation prior to approximately 10−15 seconds.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Understanding this earliest of eras in the history of the universe is one of the greatest unsolved problems in physics.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The term *Big Bang* did not catch on until the 1970s.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] It is popularly reported that Hoyle, who favored the steady state, intended this to be pejorative, but Hoyle explicitly denied this and said it was just a striking image meant to highlight the difference between the two models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Helge Kragh writes that the evidence for the claim that it was meant as a pejorative is "unconvincing", and mentions a number of indications that it was not a pejorative.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A primordial singularity is sometimes called "the Big Bang", but the term can also refer to a more generic early hot, dense phase.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The term itself has been argued to be a misnomer because it evokes an explosion.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The argument is that whereas an explosion suggests expansion into a surrounding space, the Big Bang only describes the intrinsic expansion of the contents of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Another issue pointed out by Santhosh Mathew is that bang implies sound, which is not an important feature of the model.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] However, when Sky and Telescope ran a competition in 1993 to find a more suitable alternative no alternative was successful.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] is the small box to the left of, and nearly below, the Moon) – several thousand galaxies, each consisting of billions of stars, are in this small view.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] – the universe is estimated to contain 200 billion galaxies.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Early cosmological models developed from observations of the structure of the universe and from theoretical considerations.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1912, Vesto Slipher measured the first Doppler shift of a "spiral nebula" (spiral nebula is the obsolete term for spiral galaxies), and soon discovered that almost all such nebulae were receding from Earth.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] He did not grasp the cosmological implications of this fact, and indeed at the time it was highly controversial whether or not these nebulae were "island universes" outside our Milky Way.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Ten years later, Alexander Friedmann, a Russian cosmologist and mathematician, derived the Friedmann equations from the Einstein field equations, showing that the universe might be expanding in contrast to the static universe model advocated by Albert Einstein at that time.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1924, American astronomer Edwin Hubble's measurement of the great distance to the nearest spiral nebulae showed that these systems were indeed other galaxies.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Starting that same year, Hubble painstakingly developed a series of distance indicators, the forerunner of the cosmic distance ladder, using the 100-inch (2.5 m) Hooker telescope at Mount Wilson Observatory.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This allowed him to estimate distances to galaxies whose redshifts had already been measured, mostly by Slipher.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1929, Hubble, with the help of Milton Humason, discovered a correlation between distance and recessional velocity—now known as Hubble's law.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Independently deriving Friedmann's equations in 1927, Georges Lemaître, a Belgian physicist and Roman Catholic priest, proposed that the recession of the nebulae was due to the expansion of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] He inferred the relation that Hubble would later observe, given the cosmological principle.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, almost every major cosmologist preferred an eternal steady-state universe, and several complained that the beginning of time implied by an expanding universe imported religious concepts into physics; this objection was later repeated by supporters of the steady-state theory.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This perception was enhanced by the fact that the originator of the expanding universe concept, Lemaître, was a Roman Catholic priest.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Arthur Eddington agreed with Aristotle that the universe did not have a beginning in time, *viz*., that matter is eternal.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A beginning in time was "repugnant" to him.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] During the 1930s, other ideas were proposed as non-standard cosmologies to explain Hubble's observations, including the Milne model, the oscillatory universe (originally suggested by Friedmann, but advocated by Albert Einstein and Richard C.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Tolman) and Fritz Zwicky's tired light hypothesis.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] After World War II, two distinct possibilities emerged.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] One was Fred Hoyle's steady-state model, whereby new matter would be created as the universe seemed to expand.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In this model the universe is roughly the same at any point in time.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The other was Lemaître's expanding universe theory, advocated and developed by George Gamow, who used it to develop a theory for the abundance of chemical elements in the universe. and whose associates, Ralph Alpher and Robert Herman, predicted the cosmic background radiation.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Ironically, it was Hoyle who coined the phrase that came to be applied to Lemaître's theory, referring to it as "this *big bang* idea" during a BBC Radio broadcast in March 1949.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For a while, support was split between these two theories.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Eventually, the observational evidence, most notably from radio source counts, began to favor Big Bang over steady state.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The discovery and confirmation of the CMB in 1964 secured the Big Bang as the best theory of the origin and evolution of the universe.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1968 and 1970, Roger Penrose, Stephen Hawking, and George F.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Ellis published papers where they showed that mathematical singularities were an inevitable initial condition of relativistic models of the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Then, from the 1970s to the 1990s, cosmologists worked on characterizing the features of the Big Bang universe and resolving outstanding problems.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1981, Alan Guth made a breakthrough in theoretical work on resolving certain outstanding theoretical problems in the Big Bang models with the introduction of an epoch of rapid expansion in the early universe he called "inflation".
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Significant progress in Big Bang cosmology has been made since the late 1990s as a result of advances in telescope technology as well as the analysis of data from satellites such as the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE), the Hubble Space Telescope and WMAP.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Cosmologists now have fairly precise and accurate measurements of many of the parameters of the Big Bang model, and have made the unexpected discovery that the expansion of the universe appears to be accelerating.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The Big Bang models offer a comprehensive explanation for a broad range of observed phenomena, including the abundances of the light elements, the cosmic microwave background, large-scale structure, and Hubble's law.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] More recent evidence includes observations of galaxy formation and evolution, and the distribution of large-scale cosmic structures.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These are sometimes called the "four pillars" of the Big Bang models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Precise modern models of the Big Bang appeal to various exotic physical phenomena that have not been observed in terrestrial laboratory experiments or incorporated into the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Of these features, dark matter is currently the subject of most active laboratory investigations.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Remaining issues include the cuspy halo problem and the dwarf galaxy problem of cold dark matter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Dark energy is also an area of intense interest for scientists, but it is not clear whether direct detection of dark energy will be possible.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Inflation and baryogenesis remain more speculative features of current Big Bang models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Viable, quantitative explanations for such phenomena are still being sought.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Observations of distant galaxies and quasars show that these objects are redshifted: the light emitted from them has been shifted to longer wavelengths.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This can be seen by taking a frequency spectrum of an object and matching the spectroscopic pattern of emission or absorption lines corresponding to atoms of the chemical elements interacting with the light.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These redshifts are uniformly isotropic, distributed evenly among the observed objects in all directions.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] If the redshift is interpreted as a Doppler shift, the recessional velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For some galaxies, it is possible to estimate distances via the cosmic distance ladder.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Hubble's law implies that the universe is uniformly expanding everywhere.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This cosmic expansion was predicted from general relativity by Friedmann in 1922 and Lemaître in 1927, well before Hubble made his 1929 analysis and observations, and it remains the cornerstone of the Big Bang model as developed by Friedmann, Lemaître, Robertson, and Walker.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The theory requires the relation $v=HD$ to hold at all times, where D is the proper distance, v is the recessional velocity, and v , H , and D vary as the universe expands (hence we write $H_{0}$ to denote the present-day Hubble "constant").
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For distances much smaller than the size of the observable universe, the Hubble redshift can be thought of as the Doppler shift corresponding to the recession velocity v .
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For distances comparable to the size of the observable universe, the attribution of the cosmological redshift becomes more ambiguous, although its interpretation as a kinematic Doppler shift remains the most natural one.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] An unexplained discrepancy between alternative determinations of the Hubble constant is known as Hubble tension.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Techniques based on observation of the CMB suggest a lower value of this constant compared to the quantity derived from measurements based on the cosmic distance ladder.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 1964, Arno Penzias and Robert Wilson serendipitously discovered the cosmic background radiation, an omnidirectional signal in the microwave band.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Their discovery provided substantial confirmation of the big-bang predictions by Alpher, Herman and Gamow around 1950.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Through the 1970s, the radiation was found to be approximately consistent with a blackbody spectrum in all directions; this spectrum has been redshifted by the expansion of the universe, and today corresponds to approximately 2.725 K.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This tipped the balance of evidence in favor of the Big Bang model, and Penzias and Wilson were awarded the 1978 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The *surface of last scattering* corresponding to emission of the CMB occurs shortly after *recombination*, the epoch when neutral hydrogen becomes stable.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Prior to this, the universe comprised a hot dense photon-baryon plasma sea where photons were quickly scattered from free charged particles.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Peaking at around 372±14 kyr, the mean free path for a photon becomes long enough to reach the present day and the universe becomes transparent.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Mather and George Smoot were awarded the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physics for their leadership in these results.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] During the following decade, CMB anisotropies were further investigated by a large number of ground-based and balloon experiments.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 2000–2001, several experiments, most notably BOOMERanG, found the shape of the universe to be spatially almost flat by measuring the typical angular size (the size on the sky) of the anisotropies.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In early 2003, the first results of the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe were released, yielding what were at the time the most accurate values for some of the cosmological parameters.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The results disproved several specific cosmic inflation models, but are consistent with the inflation theory in general.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The *Planck* space probe was launched in May 2009.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Other ground and balloon-based cosmic microwave background experiments are ongoing.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Using Big Bang models, it is possible to calculate the expected concentration of the isotopes helium-4 (4He), helium-3 (3He), deuterium (2H), and lithium-7 (7Li) in the universe as ratios to the amount of ordinary hydrogen.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The relative abundances depend on a single parameter, the ratio of photons to baryons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This value can be calculated independently from the detailed structure of CMB fluctuations.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The ratios predicted (by mass, not by abundance) are about 0.25 for 4He:H, about 10−3 for 2H:H, about 10−4 for 3He:H, and about 10−9 for 7Li:H.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The measured abundances all agree at least roughly with those predicted from a single value of the baryon-to-photon ratio.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The agreement is excellent for deuterium, close but formally discrepant for 4He, and off by a factor of two for 7Li (this anomaly is known as the cosmological lithium problem); in the latter two cases, there are substantial systematic uncertainties.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Nonetheless, the general consistency with abundances predicted by BBN is strong evidence for the Big Bang, as the theory is the only known explanation for the relative abundances of light elements, and it is virtually impossible to "tune" the Big Bang to produce much more or less than 20–30% helium.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Detailed observations of the morphology and distribution of galaxies and quasars are in agreement with the current Big Bang models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A combination of observations and theory suggest that the first quasars and galaxies formed within a billion years after the Big Bang, and since then, larger structures have been forming, such as galaxy clusters and superclusters.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Populations of stars have been aging and evolving, so that distant galaxies (which are observed as they were in the early universe) appear very different from nearby galaxies (observed in a more recent state).
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Moreover, galaxies that formed relatively recently appear markedly different from galaxies formed at similar distances but shortly after the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These observations are strong arguments against the steady-state model.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Observations of star formation, galaxy and quasar distributions and larger structures, agree well with Big Bang simulations of the formation of structure in the universe, and are helping to complete details of the theory.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] In 2011, astronomers found what they believe to be pristine clouds of primordial gas by analyzing absorption lines in the spectra of distant quasars.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Before this discovery, all other astronomical objects have been observed to contain heavy elements that are formed in stars.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Despite being sensitive to carbon, oxygen, and silicon, these three elements were not detected in these two clouds.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Since the clouds of gas have no detectable levels of heavy elements, they likely formed in the first few minutes after the Big Bang, during BBN.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The age of the universe as estimated from the Hubble expansion and the CMB is now in agreement with other estimates using the ages of the oldest stars, both as measured by applying the theory of stellar evolution to globular clusters and through radiometric dating of individual Population II stars.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] It is also in agreement with age estimates based on measurements of the expansion using Type Ia supernovae and measurements of temperature fluctuations in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The agreement of independent measurements of this age supports the Lambda-CDM (ΛCDM) model, since the model is used to relate some of the measurements to an age estimate, and all estimates turn agree.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Still, some observations of objects from the relatively early universe (in particular quasar APM 08279+5255) raise concern as to whether these objects had enough time to form so early in the ΛCDM model.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The prediction that the CMB temperature was higher in the past has been experimentally supported by observations of very low temperature absorption lines in gas clouds at high redshift.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] This prediction also implies that the amplitude of the Sunyaev–Zel'dovich effect in clusters of galaxies does not depend directly on redshift.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Observations have found this to be roughly true, but this effect depends on cluster properties that do change with cosmic time, making precise measurements difficult.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Future gravitational-wave observatories might be able to detect primordial gravitational waves, relics of the early universe, up to less than a second after the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] As with any theory, a number of mysteries and problems have arisen as a result of the development of the Big Bang models.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Some of these mysteries and problems have been resolved while others are still outstanding.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Proposed solutions to some of the problems in the Big Bang model have revealed new mysteries of their own.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For example, the horizon problem, the magnetic monopole problem, and the flatness problem are most commonly resolved with inflation theory, but the details of the inflationary universe are still left unresolved and many, including some founders of the theory, say it has been disproven.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] What follows are a list of the mysterious aspects of the Big Bang concept still under intense investigation by cosmologists and astrophysicists.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] It is not yet understood why the universe has more matter than antimatter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] It is generally assumed that when the universe was young and very hot it was in statistical equilibrium and contained equal numbers of baryons and antibaryons.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Both matter and antimatter were much more abundant than today, with a tiny asymmetry of only one part in 10 billion.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The matter and antimatter collided and annihilated, leaving only the residual amount of matter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Today observations suggest that the universe, including its most distant parts, is made almost entirely of normal matter with very little antimatter.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] If matter and antimatter were in complete symmetry, then annihilation would result in only photons and virtually no matter at all, which is obviously not what is observed.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A process called baryogenesis was hypothesized to account for the asymmetry.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] For baryogenesis to occur, the Sakharov conditions must be satisfied.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] These require that baryon number is not conserved, that C-symmetry and CP-symmetry are violated and that the universe depart from thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] All these conditions occur in the Standard Model, but the effects are not strong enough to explain the present baryon asymmetry.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the redshift–magnitude relation for type Ia supernovae indicate that the expansion of the universe has been accelerating since the universe was about half its present age.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] To explain this acceleration, cosmological models require that much of the energy in the universe consists of a component with large negative pressure, dubbed "dark energy".
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Dark energy, though speculative, solves numerous problems.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the cosmic microwave background indicate that the universe is very nearly spatially flat, and therefore according to general relativity the universe must have almost exactly the critical density of mass/energy.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] But the mass density of the universe can be measured from its gravitational clustering, and is found to have only about 30% of the critical density.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Since theory suggests that dark energy does not cluster in the usual way it is the best explanation for the "missing" energy density.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Dark energy also helps to explain two geometrical measures of the overall curvature of the universe, one using the frequency of gravitational lenses, and the other using baryon acoustic oscillations, the characteristic pattern of the large-scale structure, as a cosmic ruler.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Negative pressure is believed to be a property of vacuum energy, but the exact nature and existence of dark energy remains one of the great mysteries of the Big Bang.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Results from the WMAP team in 2008 are in accordance with a universe that consists of 73% dark energy, 23% dark matter, 4.6% regular matter and less than 1% neutrinos.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] According to theory, the energy density in matter decreases with the expansion of the universe, but the dark energy density remains constant (or nearly so) as the universe expands.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] Therefore, matter made up a larger fraction of the total energy of the universe in the past than it does today, but its fractional contribution will fall in the far future as dark energy becomes even more dominant.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] The dark energy component of the universe has been explained by theorists using a variety of competing theories including Einstein's cosmological constant but also extending to more exotic forms of quintessence or other modified gravity schemes.
[src:energy-transformation/big-bang-p01] A cosmological constant problem, sometimes called the "most embarrassing problem in physics", results from the apparent discrepancy between the measured energy density of dark energy, and the one naively predicted from Planck units.
